1I<ue5>2I<ue5>INTERVENTION<ql>
<styl>txt,19p<ql>
<styl>indentl,1.66i,0,2.8i,7p1<ql>
<styl>capline,3<ql>
<styl>RULERON<ql>
<styl>by <m0>By PETER WHORISKEY<ql>
<m1><styl>crline <m0>Herald Architecture Writer<ep>
   <m2><ql>
<ql>
<m0>P<m2><ql>
<m0>essimism is the fashion among <m0>haute<m0> architects these days.<ep>
   No one cares about design anymore, they complain, least of all developers. Moreover, the very promise of architecture has been called into question: The pessimists believe that modern cities simply have become too big, too sprawling and too chaotic to be tamed through mere design.<ep>
   ``We were making sand castles,'' writes Rem Koolhaas, possibly the world's hippest and most influential architect. ``Now we swim in the sand that swept them away.''<ep>
   Even in South Florida, architects sometimes speak as if design had become a guerrilla campaign. These architects, for example, no longer refer to their work as ``buildings'' or ``projects,'' but instead talk of them as ``interventions.''<ep>
   But do not despair. This region is blessed with at least a few ``interventionists'' who, despite small budgets, manage to hold on to the bigger ambitions of Architecture. With a handful of relatively small projects (--) lifeguard stands, a Metromover sculpture, neighborhood entrance gates (--) they have exerted a powerful pull on what South Florida looks like. Why is this happening here? Maybe it's because South Florida cities are so young, unburdened by the weight of centuries. Whatever the case, the work of the following trio is some cause for optimism:<ep>
<m1><styl>vs,2<ql>
<styl>txt,19p,16,fgn<styl>ragr<ql>
<m0>WILLIAM LANE<ql>
<m1><styl>txt,19p,12,hvl<ql>
<m0>Beach Populist<ql>
<m1><styl>vs,2<ep>
<styl>txt<styl>ragx<ql>
<m0> The person who answers the office door is Joe, a twenty-something who until recently was a waiter at Lucky Cheng's, the drag queen restaurant.<ep>
   A bull terrier named Buster follows at his heels.<ep>
   <m2><ql>
<ql>
PLEASE SEE  INTERVENTION,  2I<qr>
<m4>--6.697 inches ( 40p4 )--from start of measuring to here--<m2><ql>
  <ql>
